post_text:
Parents and Students,

We are aware of changes to the Nutrition program for neighboring districts. I am working with NDE Nutrition Services on Silver Lake Schools eligibility for the program.

The program is Sponsored by the USDA and is allowing districts to provide free meals to all Preschool through Grade 12 enrolled students. This would include Breakfast and Lunch. This would not include - extra milk or second servings.

Once I have more information to share I will be in contact. If accepted these changes would be retroactive to September 1st and all lunches charged for the month of September would be refunded to the students' account. Meals purchased in August would not be included in this program.

Thank you for your patience as we work through this process,

Mr. Bauer

post_text: If you are still interested in ordering a mask, please get your order in by 6:00 pm today. Thank you very much to everyone who has been ordering.
shared_text:
Silver Lake Public Schools
August 4 at 2:32 PM ·

The Washington 2021 group will be selling face masks for the upcoming school year. There are four different design options available. Pictured is a different school’s mask for comparison; they will create one that matches our mascot and school colors. The mascot mask comes in both adult and youth sizes. If you are interested in purchasing a mask, please contact Miss Baker at katebaker@silverlakemustangs.org or any Washington member. You may also comment on this post or fill out the form below. Each mask will be $8.00. If paying with a check, please make it out to Silver Lake Public Schools. When they arrive, masks can be picked up from the high school or elementary or delivered. If there are enough people interested, we will be able to put an order in to hopefully have by the time school begins.

Mask options are the following: Mustang (Adult), Mustang (Child), Rainbow, Cheetah, Camo

post_text:
2020 KINDERGARTEN PARENTS

On August 7th we are inviting all new kindergarteners to come for a visit starting at 9:00 am and ending at 11:00 am. This day will run much like we would do during the end of a school year. The children will experience what kindergarten will be like when school starts. The summer preschool students will be bussed to the elementary and home as they have been with the exception of the afternoon summer preschool students. The afternoon preschool summer school students will be picked up in the morning, attend kindergarten roundup and then be bussed home. There will be no afternoon preschool summer school on that date, Friday, August 7th, 2020.

All students will have their temperatures taken when they enter the building.

text:
2020 KINDERGARTEN PARENTS

On August 7th we are inviting all new kindergarteners to come for a visit starting at 9:00 am and ending at 11:00 am. This day will run much like we would do during the end of a school year. The children will experience what kindergarten will be like when school starts. The summer preschool students will be bussed to the elementary and home as they have been with the exception of the afternoon summer preschool students. The afternoon preschool summer school students will be picked up in the morning, attend kindergarten roundup and then be bussed home. There will be no afternoon preschool summer school on that date, Friday, August 7th, 2020.

All students will have their temperatures taken when they enter the building.

There will be no transportation provided for the students who are not attending the preschool summer school.

If your future kindergartener is unable to attend the roundup, please notify the elementary at 402-756-1311.

post_text:
Senior Parents and Class of 2020

As graduation approaches Saturday it is very important that we all take ownership in our responsibilities to the success of this event. Safety being the number one concern.

PLEASE make sure that any family members that may be attending have not tested positive for COVID-19 or been exposed to anyone who has. This day is for our graduates and their safety is the most important thing to me.

If you or any family members are experiencing symptoms of COVID-19 (Cough, Fever, Chills, Muscle pain, shortness of breath or difficulty breathing, sore throat, new loss of taste or smell please stay home and encourage your family members who are experiencing them to stay home.

We have taken a great deal of steps on our end to assure that this event can be held, you are responsible for the people who are attending on behalf of your graduate. Please make informed and responsible decisions for the health and safety of all involved.

We plan to live-stream the graduation on our schools Facebook page for anyone who cannot attend.

Parents,

Year-end check in for grades 3 through 12 student computers and text books will be on Tuesday, May 26th and Wednesday, May 27th at the elementary in Bladen from 6:30 a.m. – 6:30 p.m. We will have a table set up at the outside door of the music room on the Southeast corner of the building. Please make sure that you have all items with you. (Computer, Case, Charger, textbooks, library books and any other school materials)

The meal program will continue to run through the summer months. If you are receiving meals and would like removed from the drop-offs please contact one of the buildings to have your family removed. We will deliver Tuesday the 26th and Wednesday the 27th next week due to Memorial Day. We will then resume with Monday and Tuesday drop offs, please make sure someone is home during the drop-off time.

Thank you for your patience and support during this 4th quarter!

Mr. Arntt and Mr. Bauer

post_text: We are selling two of the metal storage containers located east of the elementary school in Bladen. We will be accepting sealed bids. Bids must be delivered to either Silver Lake High School in Roseland or Silver Lake Elementary School in Bladen by 3:00 p.m. May 22nd. The minimum bid is $2,300 per container. You may bid on one or both. Please include your name, phone number, and bid amount in the envelope. Silver Lake Public Schools is not responsible to help move the containers. The winning bidder will have until May 31, 2020, to remove their container. We will contact the highest bidder(s) on May 22nd after we unseal the bids.

Silver Lake was one of 23 high schools to compete at the annual ACTIONS DAY at Central Community College – Hastings on Wednesday, March 11. Over 600 students competed in 40 test areas during the day.

Three Silver Lake students brought home trophies for their academic skills at ACTIONS DAY. Sophomore Tyler Cumpston finished with the school’s highest finish with a 3rd place result in World History. Senior Zane Journey scored a 5th place finish in Chemistry. Sophomore Brock Karr added a 5th place finish in Word Problems.

Twenty-one students competed for Silver Lake at ACTIONS DAY. They were Samantha Bonifas, Josi Sharp, A.J. Sommer, Lexi Wengler, Nathan Acosta, Tyler Cumpston, Brock Karr, Katelyn Karr, Landon Nabower, Shaylen Beaty, Marcos Gomez, Tarissa Minnick, Blaine Simonton, Jenna Strampher, Luke Swanson, Derek Zubrod, Makayla Dinkler, Tommy Grimes, Zane Journey, Jaden Lewis and Abbie Skupa.

post_text:
Congratulations to our Chapter FFA Treasurer, A.J. Niemeyer, for receiving his FFA State Degree.

The FFA State Degree is the highest degree the state association can bestow upon a member. To receive this degree the member must submit two years of record books from their Supervised Agriculture Experience (SAE), complete the State FFA degree application and pass an interview/oral test in order to be awarded.

A.J. will receive his state degree on stage at the Nebraska State FFA Convention in April. Congratulations A.J. Niemeyer!

shared_text:
Janet's Jungle, Inc
March 3 at 12:03 PM ·

Planning your Planter!! You should choose a Thriller, Spiller and Filler. Lots of different interpretations of these are out there. This combo works great, however, you could also do a nice combination of Sun Coleus that will turn out beautifully. Don't be afraid to mix in Perennials to your Planters- nice choices are Coral Bells, Hostas, Grasses, Pugster Buddleia, etc. Another great addition would be to use a tropical plant such as a Bird of Paradise, Banana, Tropical Hibiscus, or other fun choices. I am including some great pictures of different large planters I have found over the years. Let your creative juices get flowing!!! Don't be afraid to "step outside the box" of your regular choices. Find colors, shapes and textures that you like and go wild!! (This will apply to all sales available)

post_text: Since the cost of the Washington Trip keeps increasing, the senior members are going to do a “split the pot” for the Girls Silver Lake vs Giltner Varsity basketball game. Each square is $10. We will have a winner for each quarter. Winner is determined by the last digits of each teams’ score at the end of the quarter. For example, if the score is Silver Lake 15, Giltner 12 at the end of the first quarter, the person in the square that’s 5 down and 2 across will win. If we get the entire grid filled up each winner should receive $125. We will randomly assign the numbers along the edges before tipoff. Game is on Thursday in Roseland! Please contact Zane, Makayla, AJ, Abbie or Tommy if you are interested in buying a square.

shared_text:
Janet's Jungle, Inc
February 5 at 5:45 PM ·

Perennials are more popular than ever. Perennials will come back year after year eliminating the need to replant. That being said, perennials do not have long bloom periods with which to give us viewing pleasure throughout the spring, summer and fall. You can, however, plant different perennials in order to get interest and blooms throughout the summer. Perennials are a great addition for a "pop" of color, texture or appearance to any patio planter where you just want a little something different. Great additions to your Annual Patio Planters would be Hostas, Coral Bells, Grasses, and even Roses. All plants featured will not necessarily be available on all sales options.

We have to notify Fan Cloth of all missing items within ten days of the delivery date or Fan Cloth will not send the items.
Thank you for your patience!
